# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: automatic-differentiation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Automatic differentiation is a subtle and central tool to automatize the simultaneous computation of the numerical values of arbitrarily complex functions and their derivatives with no need for the symbolic representation of the derivative; only the function rule or an algorithm thereof is required.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Auto-differentiation is thus neither numeric nor symbolic, nor is it a combination of both.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] In contrast to the more traditional numerical methods based on finite differences, auto-differentiation is 'in theory' exact, and in comparison to symbolic algorithms, it is computationally inexpensive.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Automatic differentiation exploits the fact that every computer calculation, no matter how complicated, executes a sequence of elementary arithmetic operations (addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, etc.) and elementary functions (exp, log, sin, cos, etc.).
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] By applying the chain rule repeatedly to these operations, partial derivatives of arbitrary order can be computed automatically, accurately to working precision, and using at most a small constant factor of more arithmetic operations than the original program.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Automatic differentiation is distinct from symbolic differentiation and numerical differentiation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Symbolic differentiation faces the difficulty of converting a computer program into a single mathematical expression and can lead to inefficient code.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Numerical differentiation (the method of finite differences) can introduce round-off errors in the discretization process and cancellation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Both of these classical methods have problems with calculating higher derivatives, where complexity and errors increase.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Finally, both of these classical methods are slow at computing partial derivatives of a function with respect to *many* inputs, as is needed for gradient-based optimization algorithms.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Automatic differentiation solves all of these problems.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Because of its efficiency and accuracy in computing first and higher order derivatives, auto-differentiation finds diverse applications in scientific computing and mathematics, and there are numerous computational implementations of auto-differentiation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Among these, one mentions INTLAB, Sollya, and InCLosure.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] In practice, there are two types (modes) of algorithmic differentiation: a forward-type and a reversed-type.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Presently, the two types are highly correlated and complementary and both have a wide variety of applications in, e.g., non-linear optimization, sensitivity analysis, robotics, machine learning, computer graphics, and computer vision.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Automatic differentiation is particularly important in the field of machine learning.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] For example, it allows one to implement backpropagation in a neural network without a manually-computed derivative.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Fundamental to automatic differentiation is the decomposition of differentials provided by the chain rule of partial derivatives of composite functions.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Usually, two distinct modes of automatic differentiation are presented.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The value of the partial derivative, called the *seed*, is propagated forward or backward and is initially ${\textstyle {\frac {\partial x}{\partial x}}=1}$ or ${\textstyle {\frac {\partial y}{\partial y}}=1}$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Forward accumulation evaluates the function and calculates the derivative with respect to one independent variable in one pass.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] In contrast, reverse accumulation requires the evaluated partial functions for the partial derivatives.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Reverse accumulation therefore evaluates the function first and calculates the derivatives with respect to all independent variables in an additional pass.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Which of these two types should be used depends on the sweep count.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The computational complexity of one sweep is proportional to the complexity of the original code.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Backpropagation of errors in multilayer perceptrons, a technique used in machine learning, is a special case of reverse accumulation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Forward accumulation was introduced by R.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] According to Andreas Griewank, reverse accumulation has been suggested since the late 1960s, but the inventor is unknown.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Seppo Linnainmaa published reverse accumulation in 1976.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] In forward accumulation AD, one first fixes the *independent variable* with respect to which differentiation is performed and computes the derivative of each sub-expression recursively.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Compared to reverse accumulation, forward accumulation is natural and easy to implement as the flow of derivative information coincides with the order of evaluation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Each variable $w_{i}$ is augmented with its derivative ${\dot {w}}_{i}$ (stored as a numerical value, not a symbolic expression), ${\dot {w}}_{i}={\frac {\partial w_{i}}{\partial x}}$ as denoted by the dot.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The derivatives are then computed in sync with the evaluation steps and combined with other derivatives via the chain rule.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The choice of the independent variable to which differentiation is performed affects the *seed* values *ẇ*1 and *ẇ*2.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] With the seed values set, the values propagate using the chain rule as shown.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Figure 2 shows a pictorial depiction of this process as a computational graph.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Forward accumulation calculates the function and the derivative (but only for one independent variable each) in one pass.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The associated method call expects the expression Z to be derived with regard to a variable V.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The method returns a pair of the evaluated function and its derivative.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The method traverses the expression tree recursively until a variable is reached.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] If the derivative with respect to this variable is requested, its derivative is 1, 0 otherwise.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Then the partial function as well as the partial derivative are evaluated.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] In reverse accumulation AD, the *dependent variable* to be differentiated is fixed and the derivative is computed *with respect to* each sub-expression recursively.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Reverse accumulation traverses the chain rule from outside to inside, or in the case of the computational graph in Figure 3, from top to bottom.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The example function is scalar-valued, and thus there is only one seed for the derivative computation, and only one sweep of the computational graph is needed to calculate the (two-component) gradient.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] This can be mitigated to some extent by storing only a subset of the intermediate variables and then reconstructing the necessary work variables by repeating the evaluations, a technique known as rematerialization.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Checkpointing is also used to save intermediary states.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The data flow graph of a computation can be manipulated to calculate the gradient of its original calculation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] This is done by adding an adjoint node for each primal node, connected by adjoint edges which parallel the primal edges but flow in the opposite direction.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The nodes in the adjoint graph represent multiplication by the derivatives of the functions calculated by the nodes in the primal.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] For instance, addition in the primal causes fanout in the adjoint; fanout in the primal causes addition in the adjoint; a unary function *y* = *f*(*x*) in the primal causes *x̄* = *ȳ* *f*′(*x*) in the adjoint; etc.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Reverse accumulation requires two passes: In the forward pass, the function is evaluated first and the partial results are cached.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] In the reverse pass, the partial derivatives are calculated and the previously derived value is back-propagated.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The corresponding method call expects the expression Z to be derived and *seeded* with the derived value of the parent expression.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] For the top expression, Z is differentiated with respect to Z, this is 1.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The method traverses the expression tree recursively until a variable is reached and adds the current *seed* value to the derivative expression.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Forward and reverse accumulation are just two (extreme) ways of traversing the chain rule.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The problem of computing a full Jacobian of *f* : ℝ*n* → ℝ*m* with a minimum number of arithmetic operations is known as the *optimal Jacobian accumulation* (OJA) problem, which is NP-complete.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Central to this proof is the idea that algebraic dependencies may exist between the local partials that label the edges of the graph.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] In particular, two or more edge labels may be recognized as equal.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The complexity of the problem is still open if it is assumed that all edge labels are unique and algebraically independent.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Forward mode automatic differentiation is accomplished by augmenting the algebra of real numbers and obtaining a new arithmetic.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] An additional component is added to every number to represent the derivative of a function at the number, and all arithmetic operators are extended for the augmented algebra.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The augmented algebra is the algebra of dual numbers.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Replace every number $\,x$ with the number $x+x'\varepsilon$ , where $x'$ is a real number, but $\varepsilon$ is an abstract number with the property $\varepsilon ^{2}=0$ (an infinitesimal; see *Smooth infinitesimal analysis*).
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Now, polynomials can be calculated in this augmented arithmetic.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The new arithmetic consists of ordered pairs, elements written ${\textstyle \langle x,x'\rangle }$ , with ordinary arithmetics on the first component, and first order differentiation arithmetic on the second component, as described above.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] When a binary basic arithmetic operation is applied to mixed arguments—the pair ${\textstyle \langle u,u'\rangle }$ and the real number c —the real number is first lifted to ${\textstyle \langle c,0\rangle }$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The derivative of a function ${\textstyle f:\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} }$ at the point $x_{0}$ is now found by calculating ${\textstyle f(\langle x_{0},1\rangle )}$ using the above arithmetic, which gives ${\textstyle \langle f(x_{0}),f'(x_{0})\rangle }$ as the result.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] An example implementation based on the dual number approach follows.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Multivariate functions can be handled with the same efficiency and mechanisms as univariate functions by adopting a directional derivative operator.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] If all the elements of $\nabla f$ are desired, then n function evaluations are required.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Note that in many optimization applications, the directional derivative is indeed sufficient.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The above arithmetic can be generalized to calculate second order and higher derivatives of multivariate functions.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] However, the arithmetic rules quickly grow complicated: complexity is quadratic in the highest derivative degree.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Instead, truncated Taylor polynomial algebra can be used.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The resulting arithmetic, defined on generalized dual numbers, allows efficient computation using functions as if they were a data type.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Once the Taylor polynomial of a function is known, the derivatives are easily extracted.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Forward-mode AD is implemented by a nonstandard interpretation of the program in which real numbers are replaced by dual numbers, constants are lifted to dual numbers with a zero epsilon coefficient, and the numeric primitives are lifted to operate on dual numbers.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] This nonstandard interpretation is generally implemented using one of two strategies: *source code transformation* or *operator overloading*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] The source code for a function is replaced by an automatically generated source code that includes statements for calculating the derivatives interleaved with the original instructions.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Source code transformation can be implemented for all programming languages, and it is also easier for the compiler to do compile time optimizations.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] However, the implementation of the AD tool itself is more difficult and the build system is more complex.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Operator overloading is a possibility for source code written in a language supporting it.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Objects for real numbers and elementary mathematical operations must be overloaded to cater for the augmented arithmetic depicted above.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] This requires no change in the form or sequence of operations in the original source code for the function to be differentiated, but often requires changes in basic data types for numbers and vectors to support overloading and often also involves the insertion of special flagging operations.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Due to the inherent operator overloading overhead on each loop, this approach usually demonstrates weaker speed performance.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Overloaded Operators can be used to extract the valuation graph, followed by automatic generation of the AD-version of the primal function at run-time.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Unlike the classic OO AAD, such AD-function does not change from one iteration to the next one.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] Hence there is any OO or tape interpretation run-time overhead per Xi sample.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] With the AD-function being generated at runtime, it can be optimised to take into account the current state of the program and precompute certain values.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] In addition, it can be generated in a way to consistently utilize native CPU vectorization to process 4(8)-double chunks of user data (AVX2\AVX512 speed up x4-x8).
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] With multithreading added into account, such approach can lead to a final acceleration of order 8 × #Cores compared to the traditional AAD tools.
[src:automatic-differentiation/automatic-differentiation] A reference implementation is available on GitHub.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] In machine learning, **backpropagation** is a gradient computation method commonly used for training a neural network in computing parameter updates.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] It is an efficient application of the chain rule to neural networks.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Backpropagation efficiently computes the gradient of the loss with respect to the network weights for a single input–output example.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] It does this by propagating derivatives backward, one layer at a time, from the output layer to the input layer, thereby avoiding redundant chain-rule calculations.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Strictly speaking, the term *backpropagation* refers only to an algorithm for efficiently computing the gradient, not how the gradient is used, but the term is often used loosely to refer to the entire learning algorithm.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] This includes changing model parameters in the negative direction of the gradient, such as by stochastic gradient descent, or as an intermediate step in a more complicated optimizer, such as Adaptive Moment Estimation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Backpropagation had multiple discoveries and partial discoveries, with a tangled history and terminology (see § History).
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Some other names for the technique include "reverse mode of automatic differentiation" or "reverse accumulation".
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Backpropagation computes the gradient in weight space of a feedforward neural network, with respect to a loss function.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] In the derivation of backpropagation, other intermediate quantities are used by introducing them as needed below.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Bias terms are not treated specially since they correspond to a weight with a fixed input of 1.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] For backpropagation the specific loss function and activation functions do not matter as long as they and their derivatives can be evaluated efficiently.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Traditional activation functions include sigmoid, tanh, ReLU, Swish, Mish, and many others.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] For a training set there will be a set of input–output pairs, $\left\{(x_{i},y_{i})\right\}$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Note the distinction: during model evaluation the weights are fixed while the inputs vary (and the target output may be unknown), and the network ends with the output layer (it does not include the loss function).
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] During model training the input–output pair is fixed while the weights vary, and the network ends with the loss function.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Backpropagation computes the gradient for a *fixed* input–output pair $(x_{i},y_{i})$ , where the weights $w_{jk}^{l}$ can vary.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Each individual component of the gradient, $\partial C/\partial w_{jk}^{l},$ can be computed by the chain rule; but doing this separately for each weight is inefficient.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Backpropagation efficiently computes the gradient by avoiding duplicate calculations and not computing unnecessary intermediate values, by computing the gradient of each layer – specifically the gradient of the weighted *input* of each layer, denoted by $\delta ^{l}$ – from back to front.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] First, it avoids duplication because when computing the gradient at layer l , it is unnecessary to recompute all derivatives on later layers $l+1,l+2,\ldots$ each time.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Backpropagation can be expressed for simple feedforward networks in terms of matrix multiplication, or more generally in terms of the adjoint graph.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] To compute this, one starts with the input x and works forward; denote the weighted input of each hidden layer as $z^{l}$ and the output of hidden layer l as the activation $a^{l}$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] For backpropagation, the activation $a^{l}$ as well as the derivatives $(f^{l})'$ (evaluated at $z^{l}$ ) must be cached for use during the backwards pass.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Note that $\delta ^{l}$ is a vector, of length equal to the number of nodes in level l ; each component is interpreted as the "cost attributable to (the value of) that node".
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The factor of $a^{l-1}$ is because the weights $W^{l}$ between level $l-1$ and l affect level l proportionally to the inputs (activations): the inputs are fixed, the weights vary.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The gradients of the weights can thus be computed using a few matrix multiplications for each level; this is backpropagation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Multiplying starting from $\nabla _{a^{L}}C$ – propagating the error *backwards* – means that each step simply multiplies a vector ( $\delta ^{l}$ ) by the matrices of weights $(W^{l})^{T}$ and derivatives of activations $(f^{l-1})'$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] By contrast, multiplying forwards, starting from the changes at an earlier layer, means that each multiplication multiplies a *matrix* by a *matrix*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] For more general graphs, and other advanced variations, backpropagation can be understood in terms of automatic differentiation, where backpropagation is a special case of reverse accumulation (or "reverse mode").
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The goal of any supervised learning algorithm is to find a function that best maps a set of inputs to their correct output.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The motivation for backpropagation is to train a multi-layered neural network such that it can learn the appropriate internal representations to allow it to learn any arbitrary mapping of input to output.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] To understand the mathematical derivation of the backpropagation algorithm, it helps to first develop some intuition about the relationship between the actual output of a neuron and the correct output for a particular training example.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Consider a simple neural network with two input units, one output unit and no hidden units, and in which each neuron uses a linear output (unlike most work on neural networks, in which mapping from inputs to outputs is non-linear) that is the weighted sum of its input.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Initially, before training, the weights will be set randomly.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Then the neuron learns from training examples, which in this case consist of a set of tuples $(x_{1},x_{2},t)$ where $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ are the inputs to the network and t is the correct output (the output the network should produce given those inputs, when it has been trained).
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The initial network, given $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ , will compute an output y that likely differs from t (given random weights).
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] A loss function $L(t,y)$ is used for measuring the discrepancy between the target output t and the computed output y.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] For regression analysis problems the squared error can be used as a loss function, for classification the categorical cross-entropy can be used.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Consider the network on a single training case: $(1,1,0)$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Thus, the input $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ are 1 and 1 respectively and the correct output, t is 0.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Now if the relation is plotted between the network's output y on the horizontal axis and the error E on the vertical axis, the result is a parabola.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The minimum of the parabola corresponds to the output y which minimizes the error E.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] For a single training case, the minimum also touches the horizontal axis, which means the error will be zero and the network can produce an output y that exactly matches the target output t.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Therefore, the problem of mapping inputs to outputs can be reduced to an optimization problem of finding a function that will produce the minimal error.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] where $w_{1}$ and $w_{2}$ are the weights on the connection from the input units to the output unit.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Therefore, the error also depends on the incoming weights to the neuron, which is ultimately what needs to be changed in the network to enable learning.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Then, the loss function E takes the form of a parabolic cylinder with its base directed along $w_{1}=-w_{2}$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Since all sets of weights that satisfy $w_{1}=-w_{2}$ minimize the loss function, in this case additional constraints are required to converge to a unique solution.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Additional constraints could either be generated by setting specific conditions to the weights, or by injecting additional training data.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] One commonly used algorithm to find the set of weights that minimizes the error is gradient descent.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] By backpropagation, the steepest descent direction is calculated of the loss function versus the present synaptic weights.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Then, the weights can be modified along the steepest descent direction, and the error is minimized in an efficient way.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The gradient descent method involves calculating the derivative of the loss function with respect to the weights of the network.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] This is normally done using backpropagation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] is the actual output of the output neuron.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] In this section, the order of the weight indexes are reversed relative to the prior section: $w_{ij}$ is weight from the i th to the j th unit.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] where the activation function $\varphi$ is non-linear and differentiable over the activation region (the ReLU is not differentiable at one point).
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The input ${\text{net}}_{j}$ to a neuron is the weighted sum of outputs $o_{k}$ of previous neurons.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] If the neuron is in the first layer after the input layer, the $o_{k}$ of the input layer are simply the inputs $x_{k}$ to the network.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The number of input units to the neuron is n .
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The variable $w_{kj}$ denotes the weight between neuron k of the previous layer and neuron j of the current layer.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] If the neuron is in the first layer after the input layer, $o_{i}$ is just $x_{i}$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] This is the reason why backpropagation requires that the activation function be differentiable.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] However, if j is in an arbitrary inner layer of the network, finding the derivative E with respect to $o_{j}$ is less obvious.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] To update the weight $w_{ij}$ using gradient descent, one must choose a learning rate, $\eta >0$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The change in weight needs to reflect the impact on E of an increase or decrease in $w_{ij}$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] If ${\frac {\partial E}{\partial w_{ij}}}>0$ , an increase in $w_{ij}$ increases E ; conversely, if ${\frac {\partial E}{\partial w_{ij}}}<0$ , an increase in $w_{ij}$ decreases E .
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The new $\Delta w_{ij}$ is added to the old weight, and the product of the learning rate and the gradient, multiplied by $-1$ guarantees that $w_{ij}$ changes in a way that always decreases E .
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Using a Hessian matrix of second-order derivatives of the error function, the Levenberg–Marquardt algorithm often converges faster than first-order gradient descent, especially when the topology of the error function is complicated.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] It may also find solutions in smaller node counts for which other methods might not converge.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The Hessian can be approximated by the Fisher information matrix.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] As an example, consider a simple feedforward network.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Arbitrary-order derivatives in arbitrary computational graphs can be computed with backpropagation, but with more complex expressions for higher orders.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The loss function is a function that maps values of one or more variables onto a real number intuitively representing some "cost" associated with those values.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] For backpropagation, the loss function calculates the difference between the network output and its expected output, after a training example has propagated through the network.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The mathematical expression of the loss function must fulfill two conditions in order for it to be possibly used in backpropagation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The first is that it can be written as an average ${\textstyle E={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{x}E_{x}}$ over error functions ${\textstyle E_{x}}$ , for ${\textstyle n}$ individual training examples, ${\textstyle x}$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The reason for this assumption is that the backpropagation algorithm calculates the gradient of the error function for a single training example, which needs to be generalized to the overall error function.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The second assumption is that it can be written as a function of the outputs from the neural network.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Select an error function $E(y,y')$ measuring the difference between two outputs.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Backpropagation had been derived repeatedly, as it is essentially an efficient application of the chain rule (first written down by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz in 1676) to neural networks.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The terminology "back-propagating error correction" was introduced in 1962 by Frank Rosenblatt, but he did not know how to implement this.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] In any case, he only studied neurons whose outputs were discrete levels, which only had zero derivatives, making backpropagation impossible.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Precursors to backpropagation appeared in optimal control theory since 1950s.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Yann LeCun et al credits 1950s work by Pontryagin and others in optimal control theory, especially the adjoint state method, for being a continuous-time version of backpropagation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Hecht-Nielsen credits the Robbins–Monro algorithm (1951) and Arthur Bryson and Yu-Chi Ho's *Applied Optimal Control* (1969) as presages of backpropagation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] In 1962, Stuart Dreyfus published a simpler derivation based only on the chain rule.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] In 1973, he adapted parameters of controllers in proportion to error gradients.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Unlike modern backpropagation, these precursors used standard Jacobian matrix calculations from one stage to the previous one, neither addressing direct links across several stages nor potential additional efficiency gains due to network sparsity.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The ADALINE (1960) learning algorithm was gradient descent with a squared error loss for a single layer.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The first multilayer perceptron (MLP) with more than one layer trained by stochastic gradient descent was published in 1967 by Shun'ichi Amari.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The MLP had 5 layers, with 2 learnable layers, and it learned to classify patterns not linearly separable.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Modern backpropagation was first published by Seppo Linnainmaa as "reverse mode of automatic differentiation" (1970) for discrete connected networks of nested differentiable functions.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] In 1982, Paul Werbos applied backpropagation to MLPs in the way that has become standard.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Werbos described how he developed backpropagation in an interview.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] In 1971, during his PhD work, he developed backpropagation to mathematicize Freud's "flow of psychic energy".
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] He faced repeated difficulty in publishing the work, only managing in 1981.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] He also claimed that "the first practical application of back-propagation was for estimating a dynamic model to predict nationalism and social communications in 1974" by him.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Rumelhart independently developed backpropagation and taught the algorithm to others in his research circle.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] He did not cite previous work as he was unaware of them.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] He published the algorithm first in a 1985 paper, then in a 1986 *Nature* paper an experimental analysis of the technique.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] These papers became highly cited, contributed to the popularization of backpropagation, and coincided with the resurging research interest in neural networks during the 1980s.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] In 1985, the method was also described by David Parker.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Yann LeCun proposed an alternative form of backpropagation for neural networks in his PhD thesis in 1987.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Gradient descent took a considerable amount of time to reach acceptance.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Some early objections were: there were no guarantees that gradient descent could reach a global minimum, only local minimum; neurons were "known" by physiologists as making discrete signals (0/1), not continuous ones, and with discrete signals, there is no gradient to take.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] See the interview with Geoffrey Hinton, who was awarded the 2024 Nobel Prize in Physics for his contributions to the field.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Contributing to the acceptance were several applications in training neural networks via backpropagation, sometimes achieving popularity outside the research circles.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] In 1987, NETtalk learned to convert English text into pronunciation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Sejnowski tried training it with both backpropagation and Boltzmann machine, but found the backpropagation significantly faster, so he used it for the final NETtalk.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The NETtalk program became a popular success, appearing on the *Today* show.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Pomerleau published ALVINN, a neural network trained to drive autonomously using backpropagation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] The LeNet was published in 1989 to recognize handwritten zip codes.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] In 1992, TD-Gammon achieved top human level play in backgammon.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] It was a reinforcement learning agent with a neural network with two layers, trained by backpropagation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] In 1993, Eric Wan won an international pattern recognition contest through backpropagation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] During the 2000s it fell out of favour, but returned in the 2010s, benefiting from cheap, powerful GPU-based computing systems.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] Error backpropagation has been suggested to explain human brain event-related potential (ERP) components like the N400 and P600.
[src:automatic-differentiation/backpropagation] In 2023, a backpropagation algorithm was implemented on a photonic processor by a team at Stanford University.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] In calculus, the **chain rule** is a formula that expresses the derivative of the composition of two differentiable functions z and y in terms of the derivatives of z and y.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The chain rule may also be expressed in Leibniz's notation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] If a variable z depends on the variable y, which itself depends on the variable x (that is, y and z are dependent variables), then z depends on x as well, via the intermediate variable y.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] In this case, the chain rule is expressed as ${\frac {dz}{dx}}={\frac {dz}{dy}}\cdot {\frac {dy}{dx}},$ and $\left.{\frac {dz}{dx}}\right|_{x}=\left.{\frac {dz}{dy}}\right|_{y(x)}\cdot \left.{\frac {dy}{dx}}\right|_{x},$ for indicating at which points the derivatives have to be evaluated.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] In integration, the counterpart to the chain rule is the substitution rule.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Intuitively, the chain rule states that knowing the instantaneous rate of change of *z* relative to *y* and that of *y* relative to *x* allows one to calculate the instantaneous rate of change of *z* relative to *x* as the product of the two rates of change.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The relationship between this example and the chain rule is as follows.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Let z, y and x be the (variable) positions of the car, the bicycle, and the walking man, respectively.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The chain rule seems to have first been used by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] He used it to calculate the derivative of ${\sqrt {a+bz+cz^{2}}}$ as the composite of the square root function and the function $a+bz+cz^{2}\!$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] He first mentioned it in a 1676 memoir (with a sign error in the calculation).
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The common notation of the chain rule is due to Leibniz.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Guillaume de l'Hôpital used the chain rule implicitly in his *Analyse des infiniment petits*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The chain rule does not appear in any of Leonhard Euler's analysis books, even though they were written over a hundred years after Leibniz's discovery.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] It is believed that the first "modern" version of the chain rule appears in Lagrange's 1797 *Théorie des fonctions analytiques*; it also appears in Cauchy's 1823 *Résumé des Leçons données a L’École Royale Polytechnique sur Le Calcul Infinitesimal*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The simplest form of the chain rule is for real-valued functions of one real variable.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The chain rule can be applied to composites of more than two functions.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] To take the derivative of a composite of more than two functions, notice that the composite of f, g, and *h* (in that order) is the composite of f with *g* ∘ *h*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The chain rule states that to compute the derivative of *f* ∘ *g* ∘ *h*, it is sufficient to compute the derivative of *f* and the derivative of *g* ∘ *h*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The derivative of f can be calculated directly, and the derivative of *g* ∘ *h* can be calculated by applying the chain rule again.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Another way of computing this derivative is to view the composite function *f* ∘ *g* ∘ *h* as the composite of *f* ∘ *g* and *h*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] This is the same as what was computed above.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Sometimes, it is necessary to differentiate an arbitrarily long composition of the form $f_{1}\circ f_{2}\circ \cdots \circ f_{n-1}\circ f_{n}\!$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The chain rule can be used to derive some well-known differentiation rules.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] For example, the quotient rule is a consequence of the chain rule and the product rule.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] To compute the derivative of 1/*g*(*x*), notice that it is the composite of g with the reciprocal function, that is, the function that sends x to 1/*x*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The derivative of the reciprocal function is $-1/x^{2}\!$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Suppose that *y* = *g*(*x*) has an inverse function.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Call its inverse function f so that we have *x* = *f*(*y*).
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] There is a formula for the derivative of f in terms of the derivative of g.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] And because the functions $f(g(x))$ and x are equal, their derivatives must be equal.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The derivative of x is the constant function with value 1, and the derivative of $f(g(x))$ is determined by the chain rule.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] To express f' as a function of an independent variable y, we substitute $f(y)$ for x wherever it appears.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] For example, consider the function *g*(*x*) = *e**x*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] This formula is true whenever g is differentiable and its inverse f is also differentiable.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] This formula can fail when one of these conditions is not true.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Its inverse is *f*(*y*) = *y*1/3, which is not differentiable at zero.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] If we attempt to use the above formula to compute the derivative of f at zero, then we must evaluate 1/*g*′(*f*(0)).
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Since *f*(0) = 0 and *g*′(0) = 0, we must evaluate 1/0, which is undefined.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Therefore, the formula fails in this case.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] This is not surprising because f is not differentiable at zero.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The chain rule forms the basis of the backpropagation algorithm, which is used in gradient descent of neural networks in deep learning (artificial intelligence).
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Faà di Bruno's formula generalizes the chain rule to higher derivatives.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Assume for the moment that $g(x)\!$ does not equal $g(a)$ for any x near a .
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] If g oscillates near a, then it might happen that no matter how close one gets to a, there is always an even closer x such that *g*(*x*) = *g*(*a*).
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] For example, this happens near *a* = 0 for the continuous function g defined by *g*(*x*) = 0 for *x* = 0 and *g*(*x*) = *x*2 sin(1/*x*) otherwise.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Whenever this happens, the above expression is undefined because it involves division by zero.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Whenever *g*(*x*) is not equal to *g*(*a*), this is clear because the factors of *g*(*x*) − *g*(*a*) cancel.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] When *g*(*x*) equals *g*(*a*), then the difference quotient for *f* ∘ *g* is zero because *f*(*g*(*x*)) equals *f*(*g*(*a*)), and the above product is zero because it equals *f*′(*g*(*a*)) times zero.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] So the above product is always equal to the difference quotient, and to show that the derivative of *f* ∘ *g* at *a* exists and to determine its value, we need only show that the limit as *x* goes to *a* of the above product exists and determine its value.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] To do this, recall that the limit of a product exists if the limits of its factors exist.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] When this happens, the limit of the product of these two factors will equal the product of the limits of the factors.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The latter is the difference quotient for g at a, and because g is differentiable at a by assumption, its limit as x tends to a exists and equals *g*′(*a*).
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] As for *Q*(*g*(*x*)), notice that *Q* is defined wherever *f* is.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Furthermore, *f* is differentiable at *g*(*a*) by assumption, so *Q* is continuous at *g*(*a*), by definition of the derivative.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The function g is continuous at a because it is differentiable at a, and therefore *Q* ∘ *g* is continuous at a.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] This shows that the limits of both factors exist and that they equal *f*′(*g*(*a*)) and *g*′(*a*), respectively.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Another way of proving the chain rule is to measure the error in the linear approximation determined by the derivative.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] This proof has the advantage that it generalizes to several variables.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] In the situation of the chain rule, such a function *ε* exists because *g* is assumed to be differentiable at *a*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Again by assumption, a similar function also exists for *f* at *g*(*a*).
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Calling this function *η*, we have $f(g(a)+k)-f(g(a))=f'(g(a))k+\eta (k)k.$ The above definition imposes no constraints on *η*(0), even though it is assumed that *η*(*k*) tends to zero as *k* tends to zero.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] If we set *η*(0) = 0, then *η* is continuous at 0.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Proving the theorem requires studying the difference *f*(*g*(*a* + *h*)) − *f*(*g*(*a*)) as *h* tends to zero.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The first step is to substitute for *g*(*a* + *h*) using the definition of differentiability of *g* at *a*: $f(g(a+h))-f(g(a))=f(g(a)+g'(a)h+\varepsilon (h)h)-f(g(a)).$ The next step is to use the definition of differentiability of *f* at *g*(*a*).
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] This requires a term of the form *f*(*g*(*a*) + *k*) for some *k*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] In the above equation, the correct *k* varies with *h*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Applying the definition of the derivative gives: $f(g(a)+k_{h})-f(g(a))=f'(g(a))k_{h}+\eta (k_{h})k_{h}.$ To study the behavior of this expression as *h* tends to zero, expand *k**h*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] After regrouping the terms, the right-hand side becomes: $f'(g(a))g'(a)h+[f'(g(a))\varepsilon (h)+\eta (k_{h})g'(a)+\eta (k_{h})\varepsilon (h)]h.$ Because *ε*(*h*) and *η*(*k**h*) tend to zero as *h* tends to zero, the first two bracketed terms tend to zero as *h* tends to zero.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Applying the same theorem on products of limits as in the first proof, the third bracketed term also tends zero.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Because the above expression is equal to the difference *f*(*g*(*a* + *h*)) − *f*(*g*(*a*)), by the definition of the derivative *f* ∘ *g* is differentiable at *a* and its derivative is *f*′(*g*(*a*)) *g*′(*a*).
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The role of *Q* in the first proof is played by *η* in this proof.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] They are related by the equation: $Q(y)=f'(g(a))+\eta (y-g(a)).$ The need to define *Q* at *g*(*a*) is analogous to the need to define *η* at zero.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Constantin Carathéodory's alternative definition of the differentiability of a function can be used to give an elegant proof of the chain rule.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Under this definition, a function f is differentiable at a point a if and only if there is a function q, continuous at a and such that *f*(*x*) − *f*(*a*) = *q*(*x*)(*x* − *a*).
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] There is at most one such function, and if f is differentiable at a then *f* ′(*a*) = *q*(*a*).
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] This method of factoring also allows a unified approach to stronger forms of differentiability, when the derivative is required to be Lipschitz continuous, Hölder continuous, etc.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Differentiation itself can be viewed as the polynomial remainder theorem (the little Bézout theorem, or factor theorem), generalized to an appropriate class of functions.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The full generalization of the chain rule to multi-variable functions (such as $f\colon \mathbb {R} ^{m}\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ) is rather technical.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] As this case occurs often in the study of functions of a single variable, it is worth describing it separately.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Let $f\colon \mathbb {R} ^{k}\to \mathbb {R}$ , and $g_{i}\colon \mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R}$ for each $i=1,2,\dots ,k.$ To write the chain rule for the composition of functions $x\mapsto f(g_{1}(x),\dots ,g_{k}(x)),$ one needs the partial derivatives of f with respect to its k arguments.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The usual notations for partial derivatives involve names for the arguments of the function.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] As these arguments are not named in the above formula, it is simpler and clearer to use *D*-Notation, and to denote by $D_{i}f$ the partial derivative of f with respect to its ith argument, and by $D_{i}f(z)$ the value of this derivative at z.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The simplest way for writing the chain rule in the general case is to use the total derivative, which is a linear transformation that captures all directional derivatives in a single formula.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] These two derivatives are linear transformations **R***n* → **R***m* and **R***m* → **R***k*, respectively, so they can be composed.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Because the total derivative is a linear transformation, the functions appearing in the formula can be rewritten as matrices.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The matrix corresponding to a total derivative is called a Jacobian matrix, and the composite of two derivatives corresponds to the product of their Jacobian matrices.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] That is, the Jacobian of a composite function is the product of the Jacobians of the composed functions (evaluated at the appropriate points).
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The higher-dimensional chain rule is a generalization of the one-dimensional chain rule.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] In the language of linear transformations, *D**a*(*g*) is the function which scales a vector by a factor of *g*′(*a*) and *D**g*(*a*)(*f*) is the function which scales a vector by a factor of *f*′(*g*(*a*)).
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The chain rule says that the composite of these two linear transformations is the linear transformation *D**a*(*f* ∘ *g*), and therefore it is the function that scales a vector by *f*′(*g*(*a*))⋅*g*′(*a*).
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The chain rule for total derivatives implies a chain rule for partial derivatives.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Recall that when the total derivative exists, the partial derivative in the i-th coordinate direction is found by multiplying the Jacobian matrix by the i-th basis vector.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] In the special case where *k* = 1, so that *f* is a real-valued function, then this formula simplifies even further: ${\frac {\partial y}{\partial x_{i}}}=\sum _{\ell =1}^{m}{\frac {\partial y}{\partial u_{\ell }}}{\frac {\partial u_{\ell }}{\partial x_{i}}}.$ This can be rewritten as a dot product.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] Faà di Bruno's formula for higher-order derivatives of single-variable functions generalizes to the multivariable case.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] All extensions of calculus have a chain rule.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] In most of these, the formula remains the same, though the meaning of that formula may be vastly different.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] In this situation, the chain rule represents the fact that the derivative of *f* ∘ *g* is the composite of the derivative of *f* and the derivative of *g*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] This theorem is an immediate consequence of the higher dimensional chain rule given above, and it has exactly the same formula.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The chain rule is also valid for Fréchet derivatives in Banach spaces.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] This case and the previous one admit a simultaneous generalization to Banach manifolds.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] In differential algebra, the derivative is interpreted as a morphism of modules of Kähler differentials.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] A ring homomorphism of commutative rings *f* : *R* → *S* determines a morphism of Kähler differentials *Df* : Ω*R* → Ω*S* which sends an element *dr* to *d*(*f*(*r*)), the exterior differential of *f*(*r*).
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The formula *D*(*f* ∘ *g*) = *Df* ∘ *Dg* holds in this context as well.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The common feature of these examples is that they are expressions of the idea that the derivative is part of a functor.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] A functor is an operation on spaces and functions between them.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] It associates to each space a new space and to each function between two spaces a new function between the corresponding new spaces.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] In each of the above cases, the functor sends each space to its tangent bundle and it sends each function to its derivative.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] For example, in the manifold case, the derivative sends a *C**r*-manifold to a *C**r*−1-manifold (its tangent bundle) and a *C**r*-function to its total derivative.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] There is one requirement for this to be a functor, namely that the derivative of a composite must be the composite of the derivatives.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] There are also chain rules in stochastic calculus.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] One of these, Itō's lemma, expresses the composite of an Itō process (or more generally a semimartingale) *dX**t* with a twice-differentiable function *f*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] In Itō's lemma, the derivative of the composite function depends not only on *dX**t* and the derivative of *f* but also on the second derivative of *f*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] The dependence on the second derivative is a consequence of the non-zero quadratic variation of the stochastic process, which broadly speaking means that the process can move up and down in a very rough way.
[src:automatic-differentiation/chain-rule] This variant of the chain rule is not an example of a functor because the two functions being composed are of different types.
[src:automatic-differentiation/differentiable-programming] Most differentiable programming frameworks work by constructing a graph containing the control flow and data structures in the program.
[src:automatic-differentiation/differentiable-programming] The use of just-in-time compilation has emerged recently as a possible solution to overcome some of the bottlenecks of interpreted languages.
[src:automatic-differentiation/differentiable-programming] The C++ heyoka and Python package heyoka.py make large use of this technique to offer advanced differentiable programming capabilities (also at high orders).
[src:automatic-differentiation/differentiable-programming] A package for the Julia programming language – Zygote.jl – works directly on Julia's intermediate representation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/differentiable-programming] A limitation of earlier approaches is that they are only able to differentiate code written in a suitable manner for the framework, limiting their interoperability with other programs.
[src:automatic-differentiation/differentiable-programming] Newer approaches resolve this issue by constructing the graph from the language's syntax or IR, allowing arbitrary code to be differentiated.
[src:automatic-differentiation/differentiable-programming] Differentiable programming is making significant strides in various fields beyond its traditional applications.
[src:automatic-differentiation/differentiable-programming] In healthcare and life sciences, for example, it is being used for deep learning in biophysics-based modelling of molecular mechanisms, in areas such as protein structure prediction and drug discovery.
[src:automatic-differentiation/differentiable-programming] These applications demonstrate the potential of differentiable programming in contributing to significant advancements in understanding complex biological systems and improving healthcare solutions.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In mathematics, particularly graph theory, and computer science, a **directed acyclic graph** (**DAG**) is a directed graph with no directed cycles.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] That is, it consists of vertices and edges (also called *arcs*), with each edge directed from one vertex to another, such that following those directions will never form a closed loop.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed graph is a DAG if and only if it can be topologically ordered, by arranging the vertices as a linear ordering that is consistent with all edge directions.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] DAGs have numerous scientific and computational applications, ranging from biology (evolution, family trees, epidemiology) to information science (citation networks) to computation (scheduling).
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graphs are also called **acyclic directed graphs** or **acyclic digraphs**.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] A graph is formed by vertices and by edges connecting pairs of vertices, where the vertices can be any kind of object that is connected in pairs by edges.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In the case of a directed graph, each edge has an orientation, from one vertex to another vertex.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] A walk in a directed graph is a (finite or infinite) sequence $(v_{1},v_{2},\dotsc )$ of vertices such that each consecutive pair $(v_{i},v_{i+1})$ is connected by a directed edge.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] A path is a walk where all vertices are distinct.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] A cycle is a walk $(v_{1},v_{2},\dotsc ,v_{n})$ where the only repeated vertex is $v_{n}=v_{1}$ , meaning the last vertex equals the first vertex.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic graph is a directed graph that has no cycles.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The reachability relation of a DAG can be formalized as a partial order ≤ on the vertices of the DAG.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In this partial order, two vertices u and v are ordered as *u* ≤ *v* exactly when there exists a directed path from u to v in the DAG; that is, when u can reach v (or v is reachable from u).
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] However, different DAGs may give rise to the same reachability relation and the same partial order.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, a DAG with two edges *u* → *v* and *v* → *w* has the same reachability relation as the DAG with three edges *u* → *v*, *v* → *w*, and *u* → *w*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Both of these DAGs produce the same partial order, in which the vertices are ordered as *u* ≤ *v* ≤ *w*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive closure of a DAG is the graph with the most edges that has the same reachability relation as the DAG.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] It has an edge *u* → *v* for every pair of vertices (u, v) in the reachability relation ≤ of the DAG, and may therefore be thought of as a direct translation of the reachability relation ≤ into graph-theoretic terms.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In this way, every finite partially ordered set can be represented as a DAG.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive reduction of a DAG is the graph with the fewest edges that has the same reachability relation as the DAG.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] It has an edge *u* → *v* for every pair of vertices (u, v) in the covering relation of the reachability relation ≤ of the DAG.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] It is a subgraph of the DAG, formed by discarding the edges *u* → *v* for which the DAG also contains a longer directed path from u to v.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Like the transitive closure, the transitive reduction is uniquely defined for DAGs.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In contrast, for a directed graph that is not acyclic, there can be more than one minimal subgraph with the same reachability relation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Transitive reductions are useful in visualizing the partial orders they represent, because they have fewer edges than other graphs representing the same orders and therefore lead to simpler graph drawings.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] A Hasse diagram of a partial order is a drawing of the transitive reduction in which the orientation of every edge is shown by placing the starting vertex of the edge in a lower position than its ending vertex.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] goes from earlier in the ordering (upper left) to later in the ordering (lower right).
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed graph is acyclic if and only if it has a topological ordering.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] A topological ordering of a directed graph is an ordering of its vertices into a sequence, such that for every edge the start vertex of the edge occurs earlier in the sequence than the ending vertex of the edge.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] A graph that has a topological ordering cannot have any cycles, because the edge into the earliest vertex of a cycle would have to be oriented the wrong way.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Therefore, every graph with a topological ordering is acyclic.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Conversely, every directed acyclic graph has at least one topological ordering.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The existence of a topological ordering can therefore be used as an equivalent definition of a directed acyclic graphs: they are exactly the graphs that have topological orderings.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In general, this ordering is not unique; a DAG has a unique topological ordering if and only if it has a directed path containing all the vertices, in which case the ordering is the same as the order in which the vertices appear in the path.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The family of topological orderings of a DAG is the same as the family of linear extensions of the reachability relation for the DAG, so any two graphs representing the same partial order have the same set of topological orders.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The graph enumeration problem of counting directed acyclic graphs was studied by Robinson (1973).
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] (2004) proved, that the same numbers count the (0,1) matrices for which all eigenvalues are positive real numbers.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The proof is bijective: a matrix A is an adjacency matrix of a DAG if and only if *A* + *I* is a (0,1) matrix with all eigenvalues positive, where I denotes the identity matrix.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Because a DAG cannot have self-loops, its adjacency matrix must have a zero diagonal, so adding I preserves the property that all matrix coefficients are 0 or 1.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] A *multitree* (also called a *strongly unambiguous graph* or a *mangrove*) is a DAG in which there is at most one directed path between any two vertices.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Equivalently, it is a DAG in which the subgraph reachable from any vertex induces an undirected tree.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] A *polytree* (also called a *directed tree*) is a multitree formed by orienting the edges of an undirected tree.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] An *arborescence* is a polytree formed by orienting the edges of an undirected tree away from a particular vertex, called the *root* of the arborescence.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Topological sorting is the algorithmic problem of finding a topological ordering of a given DAG.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Kahn's algorithm for topological sorting builds the vertex ordering directly.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] It maintains a list of vertices that have no incoming edges from other vertices that have not already been included in the partially constructed topological ordering; initially this list consists of the vertices with no incoming edges at all.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Then, it repeatedly adds one vertex from this list to the end of the partially constructed topological ordering, and checks whether its neighbors should be added to the list.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The algorithm terminates when all vertices have been processed in this way.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Alternatively, a topological ordering may be constructed by reversing a postorder numbering of a depth-first search graph traversal.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Any undirected graph may be made into a DAG by choosing a total order for its vertices and directing every edge from the earlier endpoint in the order to the later endpoint.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The resulting orientation of the edges is called an acyclic orientation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Different total orders may lead to the same acyclic orientation, so an n-vertex graph can have fewer than *n*! acyclic orientations.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The number of acyclic orientations is equal to |*χ*(−1)|, where χ is the chromatic polynomial of the given graph.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Any directed graph may be made into a DAG by removing a feedback vertex set or a feedback arc set, a set of vertices or edges (respectively) that touches all cycles.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] However, the smallest such set is NP-hard to find.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] An arbitrary directed graph may also be transformed into a DAG, called its condensation, by contracting each of its strongly connected components into a single supervertex.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] When the graph is already acyclic, its smallest feedback vertex sets and feedback arc sets are empty, and its condensation is the graph itself.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive closure of a given DAG, with n vertices and m edges, may be constructed in time *O*(*mn*) by using either breadth-first search or depth-first search to test reachability from each vertex.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Alternatively, it can be solved in time *O*(*n**ω*) where *ω* < 2.373 is the exponent for matrix multiplication algorithms; this is a theoretical improvement over the *O*(*mn*) bound for dense graphs.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In all of these transitive closure algorithms, it is possible to distinguish pairs of vertices that are reachable by at least one path of length two or more from pairs that can only be connected by a length-one path.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive reduction consists of the edges that form length-one paths that are the only paths connecting their endpoints.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Therefore, the transitive reduction can be constructed in the same asymptotic time bounds as the transitive closure.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The closure problem takes as input a vertex-weighted directed acyclic graph and seeks the minimum (or maximum) weight of a closure – a set of vertices *C*, such that no edges leave *C*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The problem may be formulated for directed graphs without the assumption of acyclicity, but with no greater generality, because in this case it is equivalent to the same problem on the condensation of the graph.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] It may be solved in polynomial time using a reduction to the maximum flow problem.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Some algorithms become simpler when used on DAGs instead of general graphs, based on the principle of topological ordering.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, it is possible to find shortest paths and longest paths from a given starting vertex in DAGs in linear time by processing the vertices in a topological order, and calculating the path length for each vertex to be the minimum or maximum length obtained via any of its incoming edges.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In contrast, for arbitrary graphs the shortest path may require slower algorithms such as Dijkstra's algorithm or the Bellman–Ford algorithm, and longest paths in arbitrary graphs are NP-hard to find.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graph representations of partial orderings have many applications in scheduling for systems of tasks with ordering constraints.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] An important class of problems of this type concern collections of objects that need to be updated, such as the cells of a spreadsheet after one of the cells has been changed, or the object files of a piece of computer software after its source code has been changed.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In this context, a dependency graph is a graph that has a vertex for each object to be updated, and an edge connecting two objects whenever one of them needs to be updated earlier than the other.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] A cycle in this graph is called a circular dependency, and is generally not allowed, because there would be no way to consistently schedule the tasks involved in the cycle.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Dependency graphs without circular dependencies form DAGs.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, when one cell of a spreadsheet changes, it is necessary to recalculate the values of other cells that depend directly or indirectly on the changed cell.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] For this problem, the tasks to be scheduled are the recalculations of the values of individual cells of the spreadsheet.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Dependencies arise when an expression in one cell uses a value from another cell.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In such a case, the value that is used must be recalculated earlier than the expression that uses it.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Topologically ordering the dependency graph, and using this topological order to schedule the cell updates, allows the whole spreadsheet to be updated with only a single evaluation per cell.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Similar problems of task ordering arise in makefiles for program compilation and instruction scheduling for low-level computer program optimization.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] A somewhat different DAG-based formulation of scheduling constraints is used by the program evaluation and review technique (PERT), a method for management of large human projects that was one of the first applications of DAGs.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In this method, the vertices of a DAG represent milestones of a project rather than specific tasks to be performed.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Instead, a task or activity is represented by an edge of a DAG, connecting two milestones that mark the beginning and completion of the task.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Each such edge is labeled with an estimate for the amount of time that it will take a team of workers to perform the task.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The longest path in this DAG represents the critical path of the project, the one that controls the total time for the project.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Individual milestones can be scheduled according to the lengths of the longest paths ending at their vertices.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic graph may be used to represent a network of processing elements.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In this representation, data enters a processing element through its incoming edges and leaves the element through its outgoing edges.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, in electronic circuit design, static combinational logic blocks can be represented as an acyclic system of logic gates that computes a function of an input, where the input and output of the function are represented as individual bits.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In general, the output of these blocks cannot be used as the input unless it is captured by a register or state element which maintains its acyclic properties.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Electronic circuit schematics either on paper or in a database are a form of directed acyclic graphs using instances or components to form a directed reference to a lower level component.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Electronic circuits themselves are not necessarily acyclic or directed.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Dataflow programming languages describe systems of operations on data streams, and the connections between the outputs of some operations and the inputs of others.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] These languages can be convenient for describing repetitive data processing tasks, in which the same acyclically-connected collection of operations is applied to many data items.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] They can be executed as a parallel algorithm in which each operation is performed by a parallel process as soon as another set of inputs becomes available to it.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In compilers, straight line code (that is, sequences of statements without loops or conditional branches) may be represented by a DAG describing the inputs and outputs of each of the arithmetic operations performed within the code.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] This representation allows the compiler to perform common subexpression elimination efficiently.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] At a higher level of code organization, the acyclic dependencies principle states that the dependencies between modules or components of a large software system should form a directed acyclic graph.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Feedforward neural networks are another example.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Graphs in which vertices represent events occurring at a definite time, and where the edges always point from an earlier time vertex to a later time vertex, are necessarily directed and acyclic.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The lack of a cycle follows because the time associated with a vertex always increases as you follow any directed path in the graph, so you can never return to a vertex on a path.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] This reflects our natural intuition that causality means events can only affect the future, they never affect the past, and thus we have no causal loops.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] An example of this type of directed acyclic graph are those encountered in the causal set approach to quantum gravity though in this case the graphs considered are transitively complete.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In the version history example below, each version of the software is associated with a unique time, typically the time the version was saved, committed or released.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In the citation graph examples below, the documents are published at one time and can only refer to older documents.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Sometimes events are not associated with a specific physical time.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Provided that pairs of events have a purely causal relationship, that is edges represent causal relations between the events, we will have a directed acyclic graph.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, a Bayesian network represents a system of probabilistic events as vertices in a directed acyclic graph, in which the likelihood of an event may be calculated from the likelihoods of its predecessors in the DAG.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In this context, the moral graph of a DAG is the undirected graph created by adding an (undirected) edge between all parents of the same vertex (sometimes called *marrying*), and then replacing all directed edges by undirected edges.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Another type of graph with a similar causal structure is an influence diagram, the vertices of which represent either decisions to be made or unknown information, and the edges of which represent causal influences from one vertex to another.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In epidemiology, for instance, these diagrams are often used to estimate the expected value of different choices for intervention.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] That is in any application represented by a directed acyclic graph there is a causal structure, either an explicit order or time in the example or an order which can be derived from graph structure.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] This follows because all directed acyclic graphs have a topological ordering, i.e. there is at least one way to put the vertices in an order such that all edges point in the same direction along that order.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Family trees may be seen as directed acyclic graphs, with a vertex for each family member and an edge for each parent-child relationship.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Despite the name, these graphs are not necessarily trees because of the possibility of marriages between relatives (so a child has a common ancestor on both the mother's and father's side) causing pedigree collapse.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The graphs of matrilineal descent (mother-daughter relationships) and patrilineal descent (father-son relationships) are trees within this graph.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Because no one can become their own ancestor, family trees are acyclic.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The version history of a distributed revision control system, such as Git, generally has the structure of a directed acyclic graph, in which there is a vertex for each revision and an edge connecting pairs of revisions that were directly derived from each other.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] These are not trees in general due to merges.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In many randomized algorithms in computational geometry, the algorithm maintains a *history DAG* representing the version history of a geometric structure over the course of a sequence of changes to the structure.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance in a randomized incremental algorithm for Delaunay triangulation, the triangulation changes by replacing one triangle by three smaller triangles when each point is added, and by "flip" operations that replace pairs of triangles by a different pair of triangles.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The history DAG for this algorithm has a vertex for each triangle constructed as part of the algorithm, and edges from each triangle to the two or three other triangles that replace it.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] This structure allows point location queries to be answered efficiently: to find the location of a query point q in the Delaunay triangulation, follow a path in the history DAG, at each step moving to the replacement triangle that contains q.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The final triangle reached in this path must be the Delaunay triangle that contains q.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In a citation graph the vertices are documents with a single publication date.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The edges represent the citations from the bibliography of one document to other necessarily earlier documents.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The classic example comes from the citations between academic papers as pointed out in the 1965 article "Networks of Scientific Papers" by Derek J. de Solla Price who went on to produce the first model of a citation network, the Price model.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In this case the citation count of a paper is just the in-degree of the corresponding vertex of the citation network.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] This is an important measure in citation analysis.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Court judgements provide another example as judges support their conclusions in one case by recalling other earlier decisions made in previous cases.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] A final example is provided by patents which must refer to earlier prior art, earlier patents which are relevant to the current patent claim.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] By taking the special properties of directed acyclic graphs into account, one can analyse citation networks with techniques not available when analysing the general graphs considered in many studies using network analysis.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance transitive reduction gives new insights into the citation distributions found in different applications highlighting clear differences in the mechanisms creating citations networks in different contexts.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Another technique is main path analysis, which traces the citation links and suggests the most significant citation chains in a given citation graph.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The Price model is too simple to be a realistic model of a citation network but it is simple enough to allow for analytic solutions for some of its properties.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Many of these can be found by using results derived from the undirected version of the Price model, the Barabási–Albert model.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] However, since Price's model gives a directed acyclic graph, it is a useful model when looking for analytic calculations of properties unique to directed acyclic graphs.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, the length of the longest path, from the n-th node added to the network to the first node in the network, scales as $\ln(n)$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graphs may also be used as a compact representation of a collection of sequences.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In this type of application, one finds a DAG in which the paths form the given sequences.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] When many of the sequences share the same subsequences, these shared subsequences can be represented by a shared part of the DAG, allowing the representation to use less space than it would take to list out all of the sequences separately.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, the directed acyclic word graph is a data structure in computer science formed by a directed acyclic graph with a single source and with edges labeled by letters or symbols; the paths from the source to the sinks in this graph represent a set of strings, such as English words.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Any set of sequences can be represented as paths in a tree, by forming a tree vertex for every prefix of a sequence and making the parent of one of these vertices represent the sequence with one fewer element; the tree formed in this way for a set of strings is called a trie.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Similarly, a binary search tree can be viewed as a rooted DAG where paths represent sorted orderings of keys, though it lacks the path-merging compression found in more complex DAGs.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic word graph saves space over a trie by allowing paths to diverge and rejoin, so that a set of words with the same possible suffixes can be represented by a single tree vertex.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The same idea of using a DAG to represent a family of paths occurs in the binary decision diagram, a DAG-based data structure for representing binary functions.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] In a binary decision diagram, each non-sink vertex is labeled by the name of a binary variable, and each sink and each edge is labeled by a 0 or 1.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] The function value for any truth assignment to the variables is the value at the sink found by following a path, starting from the single source vertex, that at each non-sink vertex follows the outgoing edge labeled with the value of that vertex's variable.
[src:automatic-differentiation/directed-acyclic-graph] Just as directed acyclic word graphs can be viewed as a compressed form of tries, binary decision diagrams can be viewed as compressed forms of decision trees that save space by allowing paths to rejoin when they agree on the results of all remaining decisions.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] In algebra, the **dual numbers** are a quadratic algebra first introduced in the 19th century.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] They are expressions of the form *a* + *bε*, where a and b are real numbers, and ε is a symbol taken to satisfy $\varepsilon ^{2}=0$ with $\varepsilon \neq 0$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] which follows from the property *ε*2 = 0 and the fact that multiplication is a bilinear operation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] The dual numbers form a commutative algebra of dimension two over the reals, and also an Artinian local ring.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] They are one of the simplest examples of a ring that has nonzero nilpotent elements.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] Dual numbers were introduced in 1873 by William Clifford, and were used at the beginning of the twentieth century by the German mathematician Eduard Study, who used them to represent the dual angle which measures the relative position of two skew lines in space.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] Study defined a dual angle as *θ* + *dε*, where θ is the angle between the directions of two lines in three-dimensional space and d is a distance between them.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] The n-dimensional generalization, the Grassmann number, was introduced by Hermann Grassmann in the late 19th century.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] It may also be defined as the exterior algebra of a one-dimensional vector space with $\varepsilon$ as its basis element.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] Division of dual numbers is defined when the real part of the denominator (c in the equations below) is non-zero.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] The division process is analogous to complex division in that the denominator is multiplied by its conjugate in order to cancel the non-real parts.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] 2. is otherwise solved by any dual number of the form ⁠*b*/*d*⁠ + *yε*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] This means that the non-real part of the "quotient" is arbitrary and division is therefore not defined for purely nonreal dual numbers.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] Indeed, they are (trivially) zero divisors and clearly form an ideal of the associative algebra (and thus ring) of the dual numbers.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] The dual number $a+b\varepsilon$ can be represented by the square matrix ${\begin{pmatrix}a&b\\0&a\end{pmatrix}}$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] In this representation the matrix ${\begin{pmatrix}0&1\\0&0\end{pmatrix}}$ squares to the zero matrix, corresponding to the dual number $\varepsilon$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] Generally, if $\varepsilon$ is a nilpotent matrix, then *B* = {*x* I + *y* $\varepsilon$ : *x, y* real} is a subalgebra isomorphic to the algebra of dual numbers.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] In the case of 2x2 real matrices M(2,**R**), $\varepsilon$ can be taken as any matrix of the form ${\begin{pmatrix}a&b\\c&-a\end{pmatrix}}$ with *p* = *a*2 + *bc* = 0.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] The dual numbers are one of three isomorphism classes of real 2-algebras in M(2,**R**).
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] When *p* > 0 the subalgebra *B* is isomorphic to split-complex numbers, and when *p* < 0, *B* is isomorphic to the complex plane.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] One application of dual numbers is automatic differentiation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] since all terms involving *ε*2 or greater powers are trivially 0 by the definition of ε.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] By computing compositions of these functions over the dual numbers and examining the coefficient of ε in the result we find we have automatically computed the derivative of the composition.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] A similar method works for polynomials of n variables, using the exterior algebra of an n-dimensional vector space.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] The "unit circle" of dual numbers consists of those with *a* = ±1 since these satisfy *zz** = 1 where *z** = *a* − *bε*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] so the exponential map applied to the ε-axis covers only half the "circle".
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] If *a* ≠ 0 and *m* = ⁠*b*/*a*⁠, then *z* = *a*(1 + *mε*) is the polar decomposition of the dual number z, and the slope m is its angular part.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] The concept of a *rotation* in the dual number plane is equivalent to a vertical shear mapping since (1 + *pε*)(1 + *qε*) = 1 + (*p* + *q*)*ε*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] relates the resting coordinates system to a moving frame of reference of velocity v.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] With dual numbers *t* + *xε* representing events along one space dimension and time, the same transformation is effected with multiplication by 1 + *vε*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] Given two dual numbers p and q, they determine the set of z such that the difference in slopes ("Galilean angle") between the lines from z to p and q is constant.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] This set is a **cycle** in the dual number plane; since the equation setting the difference in slopes of the lines to a constant is a quadratic equation in the real part of z, a cycle is a parabola.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] The "cyclic rotation" of the dual number plane occurs as a motion of its projective line.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] Dual numbers find applications in mechanics, notably for kinematic synthesis.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] For example, the dual numbers make it possible to transform the input/output equations of a four-bar spherical linkage, which includes only rotoid joints, into a four-bar spatial mechanism (rotoid, rotoid, rotoid, cylindrical).
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] The dualized angles are made of a primitive part, the angles, and a dual part, which has units of length.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] In modern algebraic geometry, the dual numbers over a field k (by which we mean the ring $k[\varepsilon ]/(\varepsilon ^{2})$ ) may be used to define the tangent vectors to the points of a k -scheme.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] Since the field k can be chosen intrinsically, it is possible to speak simply of the tangent vectors to a scheme.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] This allows notions from differential geometry to be imported into algebraic geometry.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] In detail: The ring of dual numbers may be thought of as the ring of functions on the "first-order neighborhood of a point" – namely, the k -scheme $\operatorname {Spec} (k[\varepsilon ]/(\varepsilon ^{2}))$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] Then, given a k -scheme X , k -points of the scheme are in 1-1 correspondence with maps $\operatorname {Spec} k\to X$ , while tangent vectors are in 1-1 correspondence with maps $\operatorname {Spec} (k[\varepsilon ]/(\varepsilon ^{2}))\to X$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] The field k above can be chosen intrinsically to be a residue field.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] To wit: Given a point x on a scheme S , consider the stalk $S_{x}$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] Observe that $S_{x}$ is a local ring with a unique maximal ideal, which is denoted ${\mathfrak {m}}_{x}$ .
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] This construction can be carried out more generally: for a commutative ring R one can define the dual numbers over R as the quotient of the polynomial ring *R*[*X*] by the ideal (*X*2): the image of X then has square equal to zero and corresponds to the element ε from above.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] There is a more general construction of the dual numbers.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] Dual numbers find applications in physics, where they constitute one of the simplest non-trivial examples of a superspace.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] Equivalently, they are supernumbers with just one generator; supernumbers generalize the concept to n distinct generators ε, each anti-commuting, possibly taking n to infinity.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] Superspace generalizes supernumbers slightly, by allowing multiple commuting dimensions.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] The motivation for introducing dual numbers into physics follows from the Pauli exclusion principle for fermions.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] The direction along ε is termed the "fermionic" direction, and the real component is termed the "bosonic" direction.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] The idea of a projective line over dual numbers was advanced by Grünwald and Corrado Segre.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] Just as the Riemann sphere needs a north pole point at infinity to close up the complex projective line, so a line at infinity succeeds in closing up the plane of dual numbers to a cylinder.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] Suppose D is the ring of dual numbers *x* + *yε* and U is the subset with *x* ≠ 0.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] A relation is defined on B as follows: (*a*, *b*) ~ (*c*, *d*) when there is a u in U such that *ua* = *c* and *ub* = *d*.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] This relation is in fact an equivalence relation.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] The points of the projective line over D are equivalence classes in B under this relation: *P*(*D*) = *B*/~.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] They are represented with projective coordinates [*a*, *b*].
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] Then points [1, *n*], for *n*2 = 0, are in *P*(*D*) but are not the image of any point under the embedding.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] *P*(*D*) is mapped onto a cylinder by projection: Take a cylinder tangent to the double number plane on the line {*yε* : *y* ∈ **R**}, *ε*2 = 0.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] Now take the opposite line on the cylinder for the axis of a pencil of planes.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] The planes intersecting the dual number plane and cylinder provide a correspondence of points between these surfaces.
[src:automatic-differentiation/dual-number] The plane parallel to the dual number plane corresponds to points [1, *n*], *n*2 = 0 in the projective line over dual numbers.
